sso]], Dorothea Freitag, [[Rob McConnell]] and Robert Van Evera. Music was written by Freitag, production was by [[Harvey Hart]].<ref>{{cite news | title=New Orleans District Birthplace of Jazz | date=20 October 1962 | page=11 | newspaper=The Gazette | location=Montreal }}</ref>\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| Title           = The Man on His Back\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1962|10|28|df=y}}\n| WrittenBy       = Karl Fruchtmann\n| ShortSummary    = In this play, produced and adapted by Harvey Hart, a lonely man is exploited when he seeks friendship from another lonely man, starring Everett Sloane and Howard Da Silva.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=xTY0AAAAIBAJ&pg=7038%2C3234451 | title=Sunday highlights | newspaper=Ottawa Citizen | date=27 October 1962 | page=TV4 | accessdate=21 August 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/film-video-sound-database/Pages/item.aspx?IdNumber=290154 | title=The Man on His Back (290154) | publisher=Library and Archives Canada | accessdate=20 August 2017 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| Title           = Protest\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1962|11|4|df=y}}\n| WrittenBy       = \u2013\n| ShortSummary    = This documentary concerns the nature of modern protesting from the violent riots of New York to the comic dissent of [[The Second City]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Weekend TV Previews | newspaper=The Gazette | location=Montreal | date=3 November 1962 | page=20 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| Title           = Black and White\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1962|11|18|df=y}}\n| WrittenBy       = \u2013\n| ShortSummary    = Concerns the racial differences in musicians' lives, based on material published in ''[[Down Beat]]''.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=xcAtAAAAIBAJ&pg=3533%2C3531380 | title=Weekend TV Previews | newspaper=The Gazette | location=Montreal | date=17 November 1962 | page=10 | accessdate=21 August 201